even made possible by literary language. Dean J. Franco probes how race is formed and transformed in literature and in everyday life, in the works of Helena María Viramontes, Paul Beatty, James Baldwin, and the writers of the Watts Writers Workshop. Exploring metaphor and metonymy, as well as economic and political circumstance, Franco identifies the potential for reconciliation in the figure of the neighbor, an identity that is grounded by geographical boundaries and which invites their crossing.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aAmerican literaturexMinority authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aAmerican literaturezCaliforniazLos AngelesxAfrican American authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aAmerican literaturezCaliforniazLos AngelesxHispanic American authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aAmerican literaturezCaliforniazLos AngelesxJewish authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aEthnic neighborhoods in literature. 0aEthnicity in literature. 0aRace in literature. 0aRace relations in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh  aBoyle Heights.  aBudd Schulberg.  aHelena María Viramontes.  aJames Baldwin.  aLos Angeles.  aPaul Beatty.  aWatts Writers Workshop.  aborder.  acomparative race studies.  aeruv.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2020 Englishz978311070474708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2020z9783110704532oZDB-23-DKU08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311069228040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781